=== Experiment 2b: the VACUUM control — is (b)'s cost partitioning, or an empty visibility map? ===
Date: Fri Jul 24 09:38:22 SAST 2026

In experiment 2 the flat twin's plan showed 'Heap Fetches: 203825' — an index-only scan
forced to visit the heap for every row because the table was never vacuumed after the bulk
load. That inflates the partitioned-vs-flat comparison. VACUUM both sides and re-measure,
so the number attributed to partitioning is the number partitioning actually earned.

$ psql -c 'SELECT relname, n_dead_tup, last_vacuum, last_autovacuum FROM pg_stat_user_tables WHERE relname IN (...)'
    relname     | n_live_tup | n_dead_tup | last_vacuum |        last_autovacuum        
----------------+------------+------------+-------------+-------------------------------
 events_2025_07 |     203825 |          0 |             | 2026-07-24 07:38:18.812865+00
 events_flat    |    2400000 |          0 |             | 
(2 rows)


$ psql -c 'SELECT relname, relallvisible, relpages FROM pg_class WHERE relname IN (...)'
    relname     | relallvisible | relpages 
----------------+---------------+----------
 events_2025_07 |          1699 |     1699
 events_flat    |             0 |    20000
(2 rows)


$ psql -c 'VACUUM events_flat;'
VACUUM
$ psql -c 'VACUUM events;'
VACUUM

$ psql -c 'SELECT relname, relallvisible, relpages FROM pg_class WHERE relname IN (...)'  -- after VACUUM
    relname     | relallvisible | relpages 
----------------+---------------+----------
 events_2025_07 |          1699 |     1699
 events_flat    |         20000 |    20000
(2 rows)


